=\\\"0\\\" errors=\\\"0\\\" timestamp=\\\"2026-05-06T19:18:15.503Z\\\" hostname=\\\"kung-fu-workstation\\\" time=\\\"0.059\\\">\\n  <properties/>\\n  <testcase name=\\\"parsingHtmlLoadsReportMessageBundle()\\\" classname=\\\"jtidy.jtidy.ReportTest\\\" time=\\\"0.059\\\"/>\\n  <system-out><![CDATA[]]></system-out>\\n  <system-err><![CDATA[]]></system-err>\\n</testsuite>\\n\"}], \"isError\": false, \"timestamp\": 1778095174644}}\n2653:[recv] {\"type\": \"turn_end\", \"message\": {\"role\": \"assistant\", \"content\": [{\"type\": \"thinking\", \"thinking\": \"**Explaining testing scenarios**\\n\\nI need to ensure my test passes even when metadata is absent, but I can't just skip or not support missing metadata. I wonder if I could catch an error from MissingResourceException. The rules seem to indicate that for ordinary resources, dynamic-class-loading patterns shouldn't be used. But if I could catch that exception, it might let the test pass, though it wouldn't really validate behavior. I think I should consider that resources need to function under native conditions. So, how should I approach this?\\n\\n**Investigating Java test results**\\n\\nI’m thinking that maybe the Java test didn’t use an agent, which could mean the dynamic access report is stemming from a native compile/run. There could be a native failure in `Report.<clinit>`, but perhaps that went unobserved. I should really inspect the test results from the JVM after the second run to see what’s going on. It sounds like a good place to start!\", \"thinkingSignature\": \"{\\\"id\\\":\\\"rs_05d581b97d6180010169fb943634088191ab21fd387f199e95\\\",\\\"type\\\":\\\"reasoning\\\",\\\"encrypted_content\\\":\\\"gAAAAABp-5RFuPhVAfzr8YmW94xTGnx7pBYVkxrP7nDesdub7C14w5mRAsfd5l2vxIO5QrtcPSIouGwaiKyVhehbpjKMscI_3DJAlWeLE_RTkqJPswaFKy4ITRm5iBMBZQGrhNOmX4hfYQYFarx2ifaaMRwfKiEv_hrvzkPgJLApvFdzXrE7xBp7KDlN3HwUwd5q9c-CTRHRyjASQ7CZ82H119INsT7KprSGS9YSdooDyH0AyFj9j6pHxhdqPyAAuYwz-YqlZOp8m-Z29zSWAFeTupag-WQBaaeFS0wRqUEqgMQTBv2tOB